"Tian J., Wang P., Cheng X.","Responses of foraminiferal isotopic variations at ODP Site 1143 in the southern South China Sea to orbital forcing",2004,"Science in China, Series D: Earth Sciences","47","10",,"943","953",,,10.1360/03yd0129,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-22444436356&partnerID=40&md5=f7f8f6670df592b71374fc72b37bfb4f","Laboratory of Marine Geology, Tongji University, Shanghai 200092, China","Tian, J., Laboratory of Marine Geology, Tongji University, Shanghai 200092, China; Wang, P., Laboratory of Marine Geology, Tongji University, Shanghai 200092, China; Cheng, X., Laboratory of Marine Geology, Tongji University, Shanghai 200092, China","The foraminiferal δ 18O and δ 13C records for the past 5 Ma at ODP Site 1143 reveal the linear responses of the Plio-Pleistocene climatic changes in the southern South China Sea to orbital forcing at the obliquity and precession bands. The phase of the δ 18O variations with the orbital forcing is opposite to that of the δ 13C, which may be caused by the frequent El Niño events from the equatorial Pacific. The amplification of the Northern Hemisphere Ice Sheet at ∼3.3 Ma probably affected the development of the 100-ka climatic cycles. Its further spreading may spur the 100-ka climatic cycle to become the dominant cycle in the late Pleistocene. The ""Mid-Pleistocene Transition"" event has localized influence on the isotopic variations in the southern South China Sea. The foraminiferal δ 13C records for the past 5 Ma at Site 1143 are highly coherent with the orbital forcing at the long eccentricity band, and lead the δ 18O records at the shorter eccentricity band, highlighting the importance of the carbon cycle in the global climate change. Copyright by Science in China Press 2004.","ODP; Orbital forcing; Oxygen and carbon isotope; Southern South China Sea","Carbon; Climate change; Earth sciences; Ice; Climatic cycle; Foraminiferal isotopic variations; Orbital forcing; Plio-Pleistocene climatic changes; Oceanography; Ocean Drilling Program; orbital forcing; paleoceanography; Pleistocene; Pliocene; oceanic regions; Pacific Ocean; South China Sea; World",,,,,,"Milankovitch, M., Mathematische Klimalehre und astronomishe Theorie der Klimasch-wankungen (1930) Handbuch Der Klimatologie, 1 (A), pp. 1-76. , (eds. W. Koppen, R. Geiger), Gebruder Borntraeger, Berlin; Imbrie, J., Astronomical theory of the Pleistocene ice ages: A brief historical review (1982) ICARUS, 50, pp. 408-422; Hays, J.D., Imbrie, J., Shackleton, N.J., Variations in the earth's orbit: Pacemaker of the ice ages (1976) Science, 194, pp. 1121-1132; Imbrie, J., Hays, J.D., Martinson, D.G., The orbital theory of Pleistocene climate: Support from a revised chronology of the marine δ 18O record (1984) Milankovitch and Climate, pp. 269-305. , (ed. A. Berger), D. Reidel, Norwell, Mass; Berger, W.H., Bickert, T., Schmidt, H., Quaternary oxygen isotope records of pelagic foraminifers: Site 806, Ontong Java Plateau (1993) Proc. ODP Sci. Results, 130, pp. 381-395. , (eds. W. H. Berger, L. W. Mayer); Wang, P., Tian, J., Cheng, X., Transition of Quaternary glacial cyclicity in deep-sea records at Nansha, the South China Sea (2001) Science in China, 44 (10), pp. 926-933. , Ser. D; Shackleton, N.J., Opdyke, N.D., Oxygen isotope and paleomagnetic stratigraphy of equatorial Pacific core V28-238: Oxygen isotope temperatures and ice volumes on a 105 year and 106 scale (1973) Quaternary Research, 3, pp. 39-55; Tian, J., Wang, P.X., Chen, X.R., Astronomically tuned Plio-Pleistocene benthic δ 18O records from South China Sea and Atlantic-Pacific comparison (2002) Earth and Planetary Science Letters, 203, pp. 1015-1029; Laskar, J., The chaotic motion of the solar system: A numerical estimate of the size of the chaotic zones (1990) Icarus, 88, pp. 266-291; Yu, Z.W., Ding, Z., An automatic orbital tuning method for paleoclimate records (1998) Geophysical Research Letters, 25, pp. 4525-4528; Mix, A.C., Le, J., Shackleton, N.J., 